{
  "texts": [
    "The definition of traits in this context is broad and may include life history traits as well as host, habitat and environmental preferences (Bossy et al. 2019).",
    "For example, the invasion success of a microbial pest (but also some insects such as aphids) could be predicted by life history traits such as dispersal modes, reproductive systems (sexual and asexual), morphological traits, optimal growth temperature or virulence factors (Philibert et al. 2011).",
    "Phylogenies can also be useful for the study of trait conservatism and the inference of missing values, taking into account evolutionary potential (Fournier et al. 2019).",
    "Furthermore, the importance of accounting for the environment when calculating the invasion fitness of pathogens has been demonstrated in ecological studies using adaptive dynamics (Papaïx et al. 2015).",
    "Interestingly, databases of species traits can also be used to identify species assemblies that are vulnerable to invasion."
  ]
}